                              .str.replace(r'[^-+\d.]', '').astype(float))

4.3 Method: Principal component analysis (PCA)¶

Why Do We Need to Reduce Dimensionality?

dimensionality reduction is a necessary method before modeling, which can avoid some mathematical or computational challenges. In addition, a large number of input features can lead to performance degradation of machine learning algorithms. In this case, PCA is one of the most popular methods in dimensionality reduction.

What is PCA?

The PCA technique first combines features with linear relationships into Principal Components (PCs). And PCs are not representative of each other. Eventually, PCA achieves dimensionality reduction by preserving the maximum variance.

Explanation:

The results shown above indicate the variance of each principal component. For example, the first PC has 44.36% of the variance, while the second PC adds 31.24% of the variance. Therefore, the information captured by the first two PCs is 44.36% + 31.24% = 75.6% of the original information.

Therefore, I can infer from the results that the first 4 PCs are required to be maintained more than 95% of the information, and the first 7 PCs can cover 99% of the information.

4.4 Method: Histogram-based Outlier Score (HBOS)¶

What is HBOS?

HBOS represents the score sum of multivariate outliers, which is also an unsupervised method for detecting outliers, and it is applied to this dataset. To better illustrate the distribution of data points, visualizition inverts the bin heights (scores of the data) and normalizes the maximum height of each histogram to 1.

Therefore, the approximate interval of outliers can be confirmed by looking at the histogram, and the outliers can be found by this method.

As mentioned above, before applying the HBOS method, the data need to be normalized so that the maximum histogram height is consistent. And the accuracy of the method can be demonstrated by splitting the data set into a training set and a test set.

In [68]:

5. Aggregating Models¶

In order to test the quality of the 11 features, the next step will be to further test them by building 10 HBOS models and by looking at the average, maximum of maximum, average of maximum, and maximum of average. If the following results are similar in the number (percentage) of outliers with the same threshold set, the quality of the 11 features is good, and vice versa.

In [ ]:
!pip install combo
In [77]:
from pyod.models.combination import aom, moa, average, maximization
from pyod.utils.utility import standardizer
# Split Data
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train, X_test = train_test_split(df_final,random_state=0)

# Standardize data
X_train_norm, X_test_norm = standardizer(X_train, X_test)

In each of the 10 HBOS models, the sums of the scores surrounding [5,10,15,20,25,30,35,40,45,50] points are calculated as the y-values. Similarly, the original dataset needs to be split and normalized here first.

In [78]:
# Test a range of bins
n_clf = 10
k_list = [5,10,15,20,25,30,35,40,45,50]
# Just prepare data frames so we can store the model results
train_scores = np.zeros([X_train.shape[0], n_clf])
test_scores = np.zeros([X_test.shape[0], n_clf])
train_scores.shape
# Modeling
for i in range(n_clf):
    k = k_list[i]
    hbos = HBOS(n_bins=k)
    hbos.fit(X_train_norm)

    # Store the results in each column:
    train_scores[:, i] = hbos.decision_scores_
    test_scores[:, i] = hbos.decision_function(X_test_norm) 
# Decision scores have to be normalized before combination
train_scores_norm, test_scores_norm = standardizer(train_scores,test_scores)

6. Summary¶

Through PCA analysis, I found that the 11 features I created needed the first 7 to represent more than 99% of the information. In other words, the last four metrics add very little to the information.

After seeing this result, I was going to keep only the first 7 metrics for further outlier detection, but all 11 features have excellent performance in the HBOS method.

In this regard, I believe I should further learn the use of the two methods in conjunction with each other. In addition to being able to interpret the results from a business perspective, it is more important to be able to combine the findings of both models.
